def plot_countries (df,clist):
  l = len(clist)
  fig, ax = plt.subplots(l,figsize = [30,25])
  for i in range(l):
    y = df[df.index == clist[i]].values[0]
    X = df.columns.astype('datetime64[ns]')
    ax[i].plot_date(X, y, label = clist[i], marker = '*')
    ax[i].plot(X, y)
    ax[i].legend()

In [353]:
def get_sorted_eigen(df_cov):
  eigenValues, eigenVectors = np.linalg.eigh(df_cov)
  args = (-eigenValues).argsort()
  eigenValues_sorted = eigenValues[args]
  eigenVectors_sorted = eigenVectors[:, args]
  return eigenValues_sorted,eigenVectors_sorted

def plot_countries_recons (reconData,clist):
  l = len(clist)
  fig, ax = plt.subplots(l,figsize = [30,40])
  for i in range(l):
    y1 = reconData[0][i]
    y2 = reconData[1][i]
    y3 = reconData[2][i]
    y4 = reconData[3][i]
    y5 = reconData[4][i]
    X = df.columns.astype('datetime64[ns]')
    ax[i].plot(X, y1, label= 'PC1 %s' %clist[i], marker = '.')
    ax[i].plot(X, y2, label= 'PC2 %s' %clist[i], marker = '.')
    ax[i].plot(X, y3, label= 'PC4 %s' %clist[i], marker = '.')
    ax[i].plot(X, y4, label= 'PC8 %s' %clist[i], marker = '.')
    ax[i].plot(X, y5, label= 'PC16 %s' %clist[i], marker = '.')
    ax[i].legend()
In [361]:
def plot_country_figures(original_df, country_name):
  df_c = original_df.loc[original_df.index.isin(country_name)]
  scaler = StandardScaler()
  df_std = scaler.fit_transform(df_c)
  df_c_std = pd.DataFrame(df_std)
  df_c_std.columns = df_c.columns
  df_c_std.index = df_c.index
  n, m = df_c_std.shape
  C_df_c = np.cov(df_c_std.T)
  eigenValues,eigenVectors= get_sorted_eigen(C_df_c)
  # 1 original time series
  plot_countries(df_c,country_name)
  # 2 The incremental reconstruction
  npc = [1,2,4,8,16]
  reconData = []
  for pc in npc:
    W = eigenVectors[:, 0:pc]
    projX = np.dot(df_c_std, W)
    ReconX = np.dot(projX, W.T)
    df_recon_origin = scaler.inverse_transform(ReconX)
    reconData.append(df_recon_origin)
  clist = df_c_std.index
  plot_countries_recons(reconData,clist)
  #return ReconX,df_c_std,clist
  # 3 The residual error for your best reconstruction with respect to the original time-series. 
  # picked pc16
  residual_error = df_c - reconData[4]
  plot_countries(residual_error,clist)
  # 4 The RMSE of the reconstruction
  pc_n = range(1,101)
  RMSE_list = []
  for pc in pc_n:
    W = eigenVectors[:, 0:pc]
    projX = np.dot(df_c_std, W)
    ReconX = np.dot(projX, W.T)
    df_recon_origin = scaler.inverse_transform(ReconX)
    RMSE = sqrt(mean_squared_error(df_c.values,df_recon_origin))
    RMSE_list.append(RMSE)
  X = pc_n
  y = RMSE_list
  fig1, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=[20,15])
  ax1.plot(X, y, label = 'RMSE')
  plt.legend()

Part 4: SVD [3 Marks]¶

Modify your function in part 3 to use SVD instead of PCA for extracting the eigenvectors. [1]

Explain if standardization or covariance computation is required for this part.[1]

Standardization and covariance are not required for SVD, SVD can take any form of matrixs and work on dimension reduction. SVD does not need square matrix or mean to be 0 std to be 1.

Repeat part 3 and compare your PCA and SVD results. [1]

SVD require fewer eigenvectors to reconstruct, the residual error and RMSE are lower than PCA with 16 PCs.

In [363]:
def svd_de (original_df, country_name):
  df_c = original_df.loc[original_df.index.isin(country_name)]
  U, S, V = np.linalg.svd(df_c)
  n = len(S)
  r, c = df_c.shape
  S_diag = np.zeros((r, c))
  S_diag[:n,:n] = np.diag(S)
  Recon = U@S_diag@V
  df_Recon = pd.DataFrame(Recon)
  df_Recon.columns = df_c.columns
  df_Recon.index = df_c.index
  # 1 original time series
  plot_countries(df_c,country_name)
  # 2 reconstructed time series only 3 singular value in total so use all 3
  clist = df_c.index
  plot_countries(df_Recon,clist)
  # 3 Residue erros
  residual_error = df_c - df_Recon
  plot_countries(residual_error,clist)
  # 4 RMSE
  RMSE = sqrt(mean_squared_error(df_c,df_Recon))
  return RMSE

Part 5: Fashion-MNIST dataset [3 Marks]¶

Fashion-MNIST is a dataset for clothes. Each image in Fashion-MNIST has 28x28 pixels which can be represented in an array with 784 elements. You can take a better look at this dataset in this link

In this part, we are going to use PCA to compress these images. The $x$ matrix below has 1000 images.

  • Create a new dataset by selecting images from only three categories (three distinct labels).

    • To compress and reconstruct images better with PCA, it is better to choose items that are similar in shape. why? [0.25]

      With the same shape, the progress of recontructed images are more accordant while using the same PCs.

  • Compute Eigenvectors and Eigenvalues using SVD. [0.25]
  • Plot the first 10 eigenvectors (as images similar to eigenfaces). What trends do you observe? [0.5]

More and more features of the orignal images are shown with the increase of eigenvectors used.

  • Create a function that requires an argument $n$ and plots a random image from the dataset, as well as a reconstruction with the first $n$ th principal components. [0.5]
  • Run your function a few times, and determine how many components are required so that we (humans!) can identify the items. [0.5]

It depends on which item to be identify by the random image, generally 100 components are required.

  • Assume you want to share this dataset with someone else. Instead of directly giving them the whole dataset, you can share the eigenvectors (some of them) and projections with them, and thay can do a dot product to get the reconstructions. Based on the number of components that you found in the last step, what would be the compression ratio for a dataset with 1000 images? [1]

Total orginal elements: 1000*784 = 784000

SVD: S = 50 1000 V = 50 D=50 1000 Total SVD = 100050

Compression ratio = 784000/100050 ~ 8x

  • Hint: compare the dataset size with a case where we only use some principal components and projections.

COUNT = 10
ROWS = math.ceil(COUNT/3)
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, ROWS * 4))
for i in range(0, COUNT):
    plt.subplot(ROWS, 3, i+1)
    plt.imshow((U[:,0:i] * s[0:i]@V[0:i,:])[10].reshape(28,28), cmap = plt.cm.gray)
    plt.title('#{}'.format(i+1))
In [377]:
def random_plot (n):
  r = np.floor(np.random.uniform(0,309))
  U, s, V = np.linalg.svd(dataset)
  a = (U[:,0:n] * s[0:n]@V[0:n,:])
  plt.imshow(a[int(r)].reshape(28,28), cmap = plt.cm.gray)
  plt.title('#{}'.format(r))
